#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:63
#, no-wrap
msgid "A Word About Configuration And Some Options"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:66
#, no-wrap
msgid "By default, LXD will allocate the required system memory, disk space, CPU cores, etc., to the container. But what if we want to be more specific? That is totally possible.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:68
#, no-wrap
msgid "There are trade-offs to doing this, though. For instance, if we allocate system memory and the container doesn't actually use it all, then we have kept it from another container that might actually need it. The reverse, though, can happen. If a container is a complete pig on memory, then it can keep other containers from getting enough, thereby pinching their performance.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:70
#, no-wrap
msgid "Just keep in mind that every action you make to configure a container _can_ have negative effects somewhere else.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:72
#, no-wrap
msgid "Rather than run through all of the options for configuration, use the tab auto-complete to see the options available:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:73
#, no-wrap
msgid "lxc config set ubuntu-test\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:78
#, no-wrap
msgid "and then hit TAB.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:80
#, no-wrap
msgid "This shows you all of the options for configuring a container. If you have questions about what one of the configuration options does, head up to the [official documentation for LXD](https://linuxcontainers.org/lxd/docs/master/instances/) and do a search for the configuration parameter, or Google the entire string, such as \"lxc config set limits.memory\" and take a look at the results of the search.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:82
#, no-wrap
msgid "We will look at a few of the most used configuration options. For example, if you want to set the max amount of memory that a container can use:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:83
#, no-wrap
msgid "lxc config set ubuntu-test limits.memory 2GB\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:88
#, no-wrap
msgid "That says that as long as the memory is available to use, in other words there is 2GB of memory free, then the container can actually use more than 2GB if it's available. It's a soft limit, in other words.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:89
#, no-wrap
msgid "lxc config set ubuntu-test limits.memory.enforce 2GB\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:94
#, no-wrap
msgid "That says that the container can never use more than 2GB of memory, whether it's currently available or not. In this case it's a hard limit.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:95
#, no-wrap
msgid "lxc config set ubuntu-test limits.cpu 2\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:100
#, no-wrap
msgid "That says to limit the number of cpu cores that the container can use to 2.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:104
#, no-wrap
msgid "    When this document was rewritten for Rocky Linux 9.0, the ZFS repository for 9 was not available. For this reason all of our test containers were built using \"dir\" in the init process. That is why the example below shows a \"dir\" instead of \"zfs\" storage pool.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:106
#, no-wrap
msgid "Remember when we set up our storage pool in the ZFS chapter?  We named the pool \"storage,\" but we could have named it anything. If we want to look at this, we can use this command, which works equally well for any of the other pool types too (as shown for dir):\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:107
#, no-wrap
msgid "lxc storage show storage\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:113
#, no-wrap
msgid "This shows the following:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:114
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"config:\n"
"  source: /var/snap/lxd/common/lxd/storage-pools/storage\n"
"description: \"\"\n"
"name: storage\n"
"driver: dir\n"
"used_by:\n"
"- /1.0/instances/rockylinux-test-8\n"
"- /1.0/instances/rockylinux-test-9\n"
"- /1.0/instances/ubuntu-test\n"
"- /1.0/profiles/default\n"
"status: Created\n"
"locations:\n"
"- none\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:131
#, no-wrap
msgid "This shows that all of our containers are using our dir storage pool. When using ZFS, you can also set a disk quota on a container. Here's what that would look like setting a 2GB disk quota on the ubuntu-test container. You do this with:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:132
#, no-wrap
msgid "lxc config device override ubuntu-test root size=2GB\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:137
#, no-wrap
msgid "As stated earlier, you should use configuration options sparingly, unless you've got a container that wants to use way more than its share of resources. LXD, for the most part, will manage the environment well on its own.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/lxd_server/07-configurations.md:139
#, no-wrap
msgid "There are, of course, many more options that may be of interest to some people. You should do your own research to find out if any of those are of value in your environment.\n"
msgstr ""
